He went to his bank and withdrew Sh300,000, which he spent to buy food and other essentials. He would distribute them to 300 families in a city slum. To Pankaj, this was a one-off act of generosity as he sought his next move.
Donation
But this donation would set in motion an initiative that would keep him engaged for the rest of the year. “I hadn’t seen the kind of suffering I saw among people in the slum,’’ he narrated to the Nation at his office. “Their agony broke me, but it also motivated me to intervene.” First, he appealed to his friends, who donated foodstuffs and money towards the cause. These he would deliver to low-scale neighbourhoods and children’s facilities in Nairobi.
Initially, donations came mostly from the Indian community in Nairobi and Kisumu, who he could easily reach out to. In the first week alone, Pankaj collected more than Sh600,000 worth of foodstuffs and other essentials. While he could have sent his team of 25 employees home for lack of business, Pankaj retained them to help facilitate the initiative.



