For thousands of slum dwellers in Nairobi and across the country, the lockdown was a devastating blow. Many of them lived off menial jobs such as washing clothes for middle-class families. With people staying at home, these jobs dried up, sinking their livelihoods.
Unspeakable suffering followed in Huruma, Githogoro, Kayole, Shauri Moyo, Mathare, Lucky Summer, Mwihoko and tens of other slums. Meanwhile, Pankaj continued to appeal for donations, opening a floodgate of aid from Kenyans from all walks of life. Banks, supermarkets, businesspeople and friends contributed money and food parcels as the initiative quickly gained steam.
Bakeries donated breads, wholesalers gave sugar, rice, cooking oil, maize and wheat flour by the tonnes while other well-wishers donated biscuits, cereals, children’s toys and sanitary products.
Money donations
As hundreds of tonnes of food donations came in, Pankaj suddenly found himself in need of logistical facilities. Shiv Temple in Westlands would offer its entire basement as a storage facility, where consignments have been received and dispatched to various destinations in Nairobi since April.





“Many Kenyans wanted to donate food but couldn’t because of restricted movement during the lockdown. They, however, supported us with money donations,’’ he said, noting that Kenyans demonstrated the spirit of Harambee (coming together) by helping in whatever way they could.



